Countries was ordered by the rhythms of human action, from the musical life of a cathedral to the measurement of time by clocks and calendars, the work habits of a guildsman to the devotional practices of the laity and religious orders. Through a series of transdisciplinary case studies, it explores the multiple ways that objects, texts and music might themselves be said to engage with, imply, and unsettle time, shaping and forming the lives of the inhabitants of the fifteenth-century Low Countries. Champion reframes the ways historians have traditionally told the history of time, allowing us for the first time to understand the rich and varied interplay of temporalities in the period.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aFifteenth century. 0aTime perceptionxSocial aspectszBenelux countries. 0aTimexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aTimexSocial aspectszBenelux countries. 4aLow Countries. 4acalendar. 4achronology. 4afifteenth century. 4aliturgy. 4amedieval. 4amusic. 4atemporality. 4atime. 4avision. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226514826423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226514826.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles